observations.recommendation:
We recommended that, henceforth,  –
The LSB judiciously and meticulously prepare the Annual Procurement Plan, to include therein itemized expenditures needed to operate public schools in the City, in strict conformity to the provision of RA No. 7160 on the utilization of the one per cent additional RPT accruing to the SEF, and provide the estimated budget cost for each expense item;

The Schools Division Superintendent (SDS), being the requisitioner/end-user, should not request for purchase of supplies or property not included in or covered by an approved APP.  In like manner, the GSO should also not approve requisitions for the purchase of supplies or property that are not included in or covered by an approved APP;

The LSB should properly formulate the SEF annual budget in accordance with the APP prepared by the SDS, indicating therein  the itemized allowable operating expenditures of public schools with the estimated budget cost for each expense item; and

The City Accountant and other signatories to the DVs, refrain from approving or signing such DVs or payrolls for expenditure items that are not proper charges to and/or not having appropriations provided therefor, to avoid misclassification of accounts.

We also recommended that the:

General Services Officer to –

Submit promptly to CAO of all necessary documents in order to facilitate the timely recording of the newly acquired PPEs, including those recorded in the RPCPPE but still not recorded in the books of accounts;

Complete the valuation of all PPE items without corresponding amounts;



Inventory Committee to verify/investigate the existence of the property items that were recorded in the books of accounts, in order to facilitate inclusion of all items still not included in the RPCPPE;

City Accountant to –

Prepare journal entry vouchers to record the PPE items included in the RPCPPE but still unrecorded in the books of accounts upon receipt of supporting documents from GSO;

Analyze the reconciling item balances in the PPE accounts and, accordingly, prepare adjusting journal entries to reflect the correct balances of the affected accounts; and

Exert efforts to locate the documents showing details of the SL balances that are reported in lump;

City Accountant and General Services Officer to –

Reconcile and verify the correct acquisition cost of the affected PPE items and prepare the necessary adjustments, if necessary; and

To evaluate if the one-time cleansing of PPE balances under COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, is warranted to reconcile all the discrepancies in the PPE accounts.

We recommended that Management to:

Strictly adhere to the provisions prescribed under Item No.  6, Section 4 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 requiring that all transactions should be supported with complete documentations;

Limit spending for representation expenses within the purview of official meetings/conferences/entertainments as provided under COA Circular No. 2004-008;

Strictly require complete documentation to support disbursement charged against representation expenses such as notice of meeting/conferences/entertainment activities, agenda for meetings, activity or program design, list of participants, distribution list or attendance sheets, minutes of meetings and brief post-activity report should be attached in every payment;

Include planned procurement with provision for catering services, meals and snacks during meetings/conferences and so the same can be consolidated to the Annual Procurement Plan as required under RA No. 9184;

Henceforth, the cost of meals and snacks to be spent for entertaining visitor/guests for the corresponding offices be charged against the monthly representation allowance of the department heads which is the very purpose of the grant of said allowance; and

Require the agency official responsible for accepting deliveries of procured items to, within twenty-four (24) hours from such acceptance, notify the Auditor of the time and date of the scheduled deliveries as prescribed under  Section  A.2   of   COA   Circular   No. 1996-010 dated August 15, 1996.

We recommended that the City Mayor to:

Instruct the office/personnel in charge of the distribution of the food supplies to COVID-19 patients and their families to submit the distribution list to the Audit Team for verification;

Instruct the OSCA to update their data base and investigate why the remaining 37% Senior Citizen did not avail the Cash Gift for the proper implementation of SP Ordinance No. 60 on the grant of birthday cash gift to all senior citizens of the City;

Instruct the City Accounting Office to reclassify the amount of P37,933,082.98 from Donations to Food Supplies Expense Account.

We recommended that the:

City Treasurer’s Office -

Coordinate with LBP and DPB to ascertain the validity of P905,713.00 and P36,656.25, respectively, or a total amount of P942,369.25 included in the bank balances by obtaining pertinent documents;

Submit all obtained documents to the City Accounting Office for proper adjustment/s in the books of accounts;

City Accounting Office to prepare journal entry vouchers to record the reconciling items with total amount of P942,369.25 in the books of accounts as supported with necessary documents forwarded by the City Treasurer’s Office from LBP and DBP.

We recommended that the City Mayor require the:

City Accounting Office to –

Record all inventory purchases as asset in the books of accounts following the Perpetual Inventory Method as required under Section 51 of the NGAS Manual;

Prepare necessary JEVs to record all inventory items existing in the RPCI but not recorded in the books;



General Services Office to –

Ensure submission of necessary reports/documents to the CAO within the prescribed period in order for the CAO to be able to prepare necessary journal entries on time;



Provide the CAO details of all inventory items to facilitate the recording in the books of accounts;

Prepare separate RPCI for Special Education Fund (SEF) for easy reconciliation;

CAO and GSO to analyze and identify discrepancies of inventory balances between the two records and take necessary actions to resolve the discrepancies; and

Henceforth, conduct regular reconciliation of the inventory balance account to ensure fair presentation of the inventory accounts.

We reiterated our prior years’ recommendations that the GSO-Inventory Committee prioritize the reconciliation of the results of the physical inventory count with the records of the CAO.

We also recommended that the: 

General Services Officer –

Submit the necessary documents to CAO in order to facilitate the recording of all existing PPEs that remained unrecorded in the books of account;

Maintain Property Cards for each PPE item under all asset class; 



Inventory Committee to – 

Verify the existence of the property items that were recorded in the books of accounts but not included in the RPCPPE and reconcile the same with CAO’s records;

Provide complete information of the PPE item included in the RPCPPE as “2004 Other Asset Balance” to ascertain its existence.


City Accountant to –

Prepare journal entry vouchers to record the PPE items included in the RPCPPE but still unrecorded in the books of accounts upon receipt of pertinent documents from GSO;

Prepare necessary adjusting journal entries to reclassify PPE items erroneously recorded under improper accounting titles;

Analyze the PPE items recorded as “Beginning Balance/Reconciling Item” and “2004 Other Asset Balance” and prepare adjusting journal entries, as supported with proper documents, to reflect the correct balances, composition and information of the affected accounts.

City Accountant and General Services Officer to –

Reconcile and verify the correct acquisition cost of the affected PPE items and prepare the necessary adjustments; and

Have better coordination in reconciling their records in order to eliminate the variances in all the affected PPE accounts.

We recommended that the:

City Engineering Office –

Issue certificates of completion for completed infrastructure projects for proper monitoring;

Submit promptly to the City Accounting Office all the necessary documents in order to facilitate the timely recording of completed PPAs to its appropriate PPE accounts; 

City Accounting Office – 

Prepare journal entry vouchers to reclassify the completed PPAs to its appropriate PPE accounts upon securing the necessary documents from the City Engineering Office;



Prepare journal entry vouchers to record the related Depreciation Expense, Accumulated Depreciation and Accumulated Surplus for the aforementioned PPAs;

Prepare necessary adjusting entries for the over/under reclassification of the two projects with a net amount of P33,605.14; and

City Planning and Development Office coordinate with implementing offices of the PPAs to ensure that all completed PPAs are included in the Annual Accomplishment Report for proper monitoring and reporting;

We likewise recommended that the City Accounting Office to coordinate with the City Engineering Office to properly record and monitor all on-going and completed PPAs.

We recommended for the City Accounting Office to:

analyze the balance per confirmation with the DOH-MMCHD and DBM;

expedite the submission of the fund utilization report to the DOH-MMCHD for the expended funds; 

reconcile Accounting and DOH as well as DBM records; and 

make the necessary adjustments in the books, if warranted, to present fairly the financial statements.

We reiterated our recommendation that the City Mayor direct the General Services Office to henceforth:

properly prepare the Purchase Orders by completing all the necessary information as required under COA Circular No. 96-010;

require requisitioners/end-users to specify with particularity all the basic data/information regarding the items to be procured that should appear in the POs by following the guidelines set in COA Circular No. 96-010.; 

refuse to process POs pertaining to requisitions of goods that are not described in detail; and

advance copies of POs and/or Contracts, together with certified copies of bidding documents required in COA Circular No. 2009-001 be submitted within five (5) working days from perfection or from the signing by the Supplier on the “Conforme” portion.

We recommended that the City Mayor require:

The City Treasurer to-

Request copies of Credit and Debit Memos from the Bank, and furnish the CAO to record the reconciling items;

Provide the CAO with copies of communications to the bank regarding request for adjustments on the auto debit arrangement (ADA)/ cash withdrawals made for the salary of a City employee;

Send a written notice to payees/check holders of the existence of the check one month before the check becomes stale;




The City Accountant to -

Prepare adjusting entries to record the reconciling items in the books of accounts, upon receipt of the necessary supporting documents; and

Record adjustments in the books of accounts to revert back the stale checks classified as outstanding checks in the BRS.

We recommended that the City Mayor advise the:

CAO to –

Prepare JEV to record the issuance of Learning Materials for students with a total cost of P36,003,786.40;

Provide a list of non-moving inventories with their Purchase Order (PO) Numbers to the GSO, in order for the GSO to facilitate the retrieval of their records;

Record all inventory purchases as asset in the books of accounts following the Perpetual Inventory Method as required under Section 51 of the MNGAS for LGUs;

Prepare necessary JEVs to record all inventory items with no accounting details;

Prepare adjusting entries to correct the abnormal balance of the inventory accounts, henceforth, verify whether abnormal balance exists at year end, and effect necessary adjustments;

GSO to –

Ensure submission of necessary reports/ documents to CAO within the deadline set, in order for CAO to prepare necessary journal entries;

Verify the existence of non-moving inventories and identify causes of its discrepancies with CAO;

Prepare Requisition and Issuance Slip (RIS) for all issued inventory items;


Provide CAO details of all inventory items with no accounting records to facilitate the recording in the books of accounts;

Prepare RPCI reflecting the existing balances as of year-end;

CAO and GSO to –

Analyze and identify discrepancies of inventory balance between the two records and take necessary action to resolve the discrepancies; and

Henceforth, conduct regular reconciliation of the inventory balance account to ensure fair presentation of the inventory accounts.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the:

a.	CAO and CHO to reconcile their records and prepare necessary actions to resolve the differences between the two records, in compliance with Section 491 (b) of the GAAM;

b. CHO and GSO to -

•	Submit the monthly SSMI with RIS to CAO for recording prior to the submission of the reports to COA;



•	Ensure that copies of SSMI and RIS were received by the CAO;





c. CAO to -

•	Prepare the necessary JEV to cancel and adjust the abnormal balance amounting to P2,530.00 in the books of accounts;

•	Recognize expense upon the issuance of inventories, supported by the submitted SSMI and RIS of CHO and GSO;

•	Submit SSMI and RIS prepared by CHO to COA upon recording of the issuance in the books of accounts; and

d.	CHO to prepare RPCI in accordance with Appendix 48 of the MNGAS for LGUs.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the:

a.	CTO to include all accountable forms still on hand in the monthly CRAAF submitted to the CAO;




b. CAO to -

•	Prepare necessary JEVs to record the adjustment in order to reflect the correct balance of the Accountable Forms, Plate and Stickers account;

•	Henceforth, record all purchases of accountable forms as inventory and recognize expense only when it is distributed; and

c. CTO and CAO to regularly reconcile their records and prepare necessary actions in compliance with Section 491 (b) of the GAAM, Vol. I.

We reiterated our prior years’ recommendations that the Inventory Committee prioritize the reconciliation of the results of the physical inventory count with the records of the CAO.

We also recommended that the City Mayor instruct the:

The GSO to –

Submit promptly all necessary documents in order to facilitate the timely recording of the acquired PPE prior to the closing of the books of accounts;

The Inventory Committee to –

Verify the existence of the property items that were recorded in the books of accounts but not included in the RPCPPE;



Conduct an annual physical inventory of all PPE of the City, particularly the infrastructure assets;

The City Accountant to –

Prepare JEVs to record PPE acquired in CY 2020 and included in RPCPPE but still unrecorded in the books of accounts;

Analyze the reconciling items and other asset balance in PPE accounts and accordingly prepare adjusting journal entries to reflect the correct balances of the affected accounts;




The City Accountant and GSO to –

Reconcile their records in order to verify the correct acquisition costs of the infrastructure assets, and prepare the necessary adjustments; and

Assign and identify the correct and specific property numbers and classifications of all PPE items.

We recommended that the City Mayor require:

The City Engineering Office to expedite the processing of claims of the completed projects by contract totaling P174,612,297.09 and issue certificates of completion for projects implemented by administration involving a total amount of P5,700,256.91 (P3,996,155.20 and P1,704,101.71);

The CAO to –

Record the completed projects identified as dormant for two to eight years with a total amount of P20,031,144.69 (P20,054,807.45 less P23,662.76 that should be recorded as repairs and maintenance) to its PPE account after securing the documents from the City Engineering Office;

Compute for the related depreciation of the infrastructure assets and prepare necessary JEV to record the amount;

Adjust the amount of P23,662.76 to Prior Period Adjustment to record the cost of repairs and maintenance incurred in CYs 2013, 2016 and 2018; and

Moreover, transfer the amount of P9,386,931.45 treated as CIP-Buildings and Other Structures to CIP-Infrastructure Assets.

We recommended that the City Mayor require:
The City Treasurer to-
Request a copies of Credit and Debit Memos from the Bank, and furnish the CAO to record the reconciling items;
Submit a Report of Unreleased Checks as of year-end to the CAO for the preparation of adjusting journal entries to reflect the correct cash balances as of year-end;
Notify the payees/check holders one month before the check will become stale;
Ensure that upon the issuance/release of a check, the payee affixes his/her signature in the Disbursement Voucher and the date when the same was received, to determine whether the transaction has been properly accounted for;
The City Accountant to -
Draw a journal entry voucher to record in the books of accounts the reconciling items, upon receipt of the necessary supporting documents;
Recognize liability for unreleased checks as at year-end instead of treating them as deduction from Cash in Bank-LCCA; and
Record adjustments in the books of accounts to revert back the stale checks classified as outstanding checks in the BRS.
Management comment:
The City Accountant committed to closely coordinate with the Treasury Office to obtain the necessary documents and draw a journal entry voucher to record the required adjustments in the books of accounts.

We reiterated our prior years’ recommendations that the Inventory Committee prioritize the reconciliation of the results of the physical inventory count with the records of the CAO.
We also recommended that the City Mayor instruct:
The GSO to –
Submit promptly all necessary documents in order to facilitate the timely recording of the acquired PPE prior to the closing of the books of accounts;
Facilitate the request for disposal of the unserviceable PPEs totaling P17,910,347.47;
The Inventory Committee to –
Exclude in the RPCPPE the PPEs acquired in CY 2019 totaling P96,125.00 which were recorded as expense/inventory accounts in the books of accounts;
Verify the existence of the property items totaling P222,659,881.65 that were recorded in the books of accounts but not included in the RPCPPE;
Conduct an annual physical inventory of all the PPE of the City, particularly the infrastructure assets;
The City Accountant to –
Prepare journal entry vouchers to record the transfer of the PPE acquired in CY 2019 from TF to GF amounting to P82,530.00;
Prepare journal entry vouchers to record the PPE totaling P978,218.00 acquired in CY 2019 and included in the RPCPPE but still unrecorded in the books of accounts;
Analyze the reconciling items totaling P119,315,007.49 and Other Assets balance of P49,506,208.74 in the PPE accounts and prepare adjusting journal entries to reflect the correct balances of the affected accounts;
The City Accountant and GSO to –
Reconcile their records to verify the correct acquisition cost of the PPE items totaling P748,640,168.61 as recorded in the books of accounts, and prepare adjustments accordingly; and
Come up with the correct property number and classification of all PPE items with total cost of P5,069,800.77 and P226,054,572.96, respectively.
Management comment:
The City Accountant committed to coordinate with the General Services Officer to facilitate reconciliation of PPE balances between the accounting and property records.

We recommended that the City Mayor require:
The City Engineering Office to –
Expedite the processing of claims of the completed projects by contract totaling P22,317,772.21 and issue certificates of completion for projects implemented by administration involving a total amount of P4,081,499.33;
The CAO to –
Transfer to the Infrastructure Assets the completed projects still in the CIP wherein final payments had already been made totaling P12,546,993.23;
Record the completed projects identified as dormant for two to ten years with a total amount of P25,661,812.05 (P27,658,138.88 less dormant CIP with final payment of P1,887,006.83, less suspended project of P97,920.00 and P11,400.00 that should be recorded as repairs and maintenance) to its PPE account after securing the documents from the City Engineering Office;
Reclassify the P97,920.00 to Construction Materials Inventory and adjust the amount of P11,400.00 to Prior Period Adjustment to record the cost of repairs and maintenance incurred in CY 2017;
Coordinate with the City Engineering Office to verify the completed projects amounting to P578,787.00 and prepare the adjusting entries to close these to the proper asset account; and
Moreover, transfer the amount of P8,355,840.16 treated as CIP-Buildings and Other Structures to CIP-Infrastructure Assets.
Management comment:
The City Accountant has partially implemented the audit recommendation.  Completed projects amounting to P25,631,001.63 were already reclassified from CIP to the appropriate Infrastructure Asset account. Also, adjustment for CIP account amounting to P11,400.00 to Prior Period Adjustments was already made. She further informed that the remaining balance of CIP account amounting to P39,665,182.19 will be transferred to appropriate Infrastructure account and corresponding Depreciation Expenses as well as Accumulated Depreciation shall be provided.

We recommended that Management instruct:

The General Services Office (GSO) to –

Coordinate with the City Accounting Office (CAO) to reconcile the results of the inventory count with the accounting records;

Locate the Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) for the materials that were purchased in previous years and no longer included in the RPCI but remained in the books;

Ensure that all issuances of supplies and materials are covered with duly approved RIS;

Ensure that all RIS are recorded in the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued which is the basis for the CAO in preparing the JEV to record the issuance of the supplies and materials;

The City Accounting Office (CAO) to –

Coordinate with the GSO to reconcile the discrepancies between their records;


Record the total amount of P1,099,350.52 as expense and credit the same under the account Drugs and Medicine Inventory as this represents the amount of inventories with no balances and were fully issued in 2018;

Make necessary adjustments, as a result of the reconciliation process, to the inventory accounts based on the existing quantities at year-end;

The City Health Office (CHO) to –

Provide details on the acquisition dates of medicines to monitor its shelf life;


Check regularly the expiration dates of the drugs and medicine inventories and dispose those which are beyond their shelf life; and

Dispose of the expired medicines and provide the details/list to the CAO for recording.

We reiterated our previous years’ recommendations that the Inventory Team of the City under the GSO prioritize the reconciliation of the results of the inventory count with the property and accounting records.

We also recommended that:

The CAO –

Secure supporting documents to record all assets which were included in the RPCPPE as City’s property but not recorded in the books;

Look immediately into the noted discrepancies and determine the factors that contributed to the total variance;

Prepare adjusting entries for the improvements made in CY 2018 erroneously debited to PPE accounts;


Analyze continuously the reconciling items and other asset balance in the PPE accounts and accordingly prepare adjusting journal entries to reflect the correct balances of the affected accounts;

Adjust the affected accounts, as a result of the reconciliation, that are determined to be under/ overstated to present the correct balances of PPE in the financial statements and effect adjustments of the accumulated depreciation, if necessary; and

The GSO immediately provide copies of the AIR, Invoice, Purchase Order and Purchase Request to the CAO to facilitate the immediate recording of the asset and Accounts Payable.

We recommended that the City Mayor instruct:

The City Engineering Office to –

Issue certificate of completion for projects implemented by administration in the accumulated amount of P3,288,431.56;


Expedite the processing of claims from supplier to facilitate the recording in the appropriate asset accounts in the books the completed projects by contract totaling P51,615,505.69, or if the contractor is no longer interested to collect the balances of the contracts, consider said balances as savings and issue the corresponding certificate of completion and acceptance;

The CAO to –

Coordinate with the City Engineering Office to verify projects already completed with accumulated cost of P3,288,431.56, and prepare the adjusting entries to close the CIP Accounts to the proper asset account and record the corresponding depreciation;

Record completed projects identified as dormant for more than two to nine years with a total cost of P30,096,648.56 after securing the documents from the City Engineering Office;

Adjust the amount of P43,635.00 recorded as Construction in Progress instead of Repairs and Maintenance; and

Reclassify the unissued/unused materials directly recorded as CIP totaling P333,131.00 to Construction Materials Inventory account.

Strictly monitor the liquidation of cash advances (CAs) by sending demand letters regularly, particularly to Accountable Officers (AOs) who are active in service, and in case of failure to liquidate the same despite such demand, withhold the amount of any money due them pursuant to afore-cited Circular;

Require the AOs to liquidate on time the cash advances pursuant to Item 5 of COA Circular 97-002 and Section 89 of PD 1445;

Refrain from granting additional cash advance unless the previous ones are already liquidated, pursuant to the afore-quoted provisions to safeguard the fund from misuse or any events that are beyond the control of the AO; and

Schedule the distribution, if multiple CAs are inevitable such as financial assistance and birthday cash gift, to give time for the AO to organize and submit liquidation reports and supporting documents before the additional CAs are undertaken.

The Local Chief Executive create a committee to reconcile the variance between the balances reported in the ledger and those that are counted per physical inventory.  Reconciliation should be documented clearly to verify that a review has been done and communicated for error correction and/or adjustments;

The City General Services Officer:

Reconcile the results of the inventory count with the accounting records;


Follow the prescribed format for the preparation of Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) which includes unit cost and total cost.  The stock code and end user/project of the issued inventory items should always be indicated and the SSMI that will be submitted to the City Accountant should be the total issued quantities per month and not the daily issuances to facilitate the recording;

The City Accountant:

Record the amount of P6,468,354.72 as Prior Year’s Adjustment, and P2,154,314.65 as an expense and credit the total amount of P8,622,669.37 under the account Drugs and Medicine Inventory as this represents the amount of inventories which were fully issued in CY 2017;

Expedite the process of recording the issued inventories that should have already been capitalized and/or expensed; and

Make necessary adjustments to the inventory accounts, as a result of the reconciliation process, based on the existing quantities at year-end.

observations.managementAction:
Management has already undertaken the following measures:




A committee was created to work on the reconciliation of the records of accounting and the inventory report;



Some personnel of the GSO were re-assigned to the warehouse to improve the record keeping of purchases and issuances of inventories;

The retrieval, consolidation, reconciliation and recording of all RIS issued is on-going;  and

Pre-numbered RIS will be used for better control.




The GSO submitted to the Audit Group and City Accounting Office various copies of RIS that were previously unsubmitted to the accounting office.  With this, the City Accounting Office credited the amounts of P9,215.21; P3,111,559.68 and P53,791,204.00 to Office Supplies, Drugs and Medicines and Construction Materials Inventories accounts, respectively and debited the same amounts to Prior Year’s Adjustment.

observations.recommendation:
The City General Services Officer submit all the remaining Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) to the City Accountant especially for those projects that were already completed;

The City Engineer issue certificate of completion for projects implemented by administration;  and


The City Accountant prepare the adjusting entries to record the issuance of inventories for projects implemented by administration, close the Construction in Progress (CIP) accounts to the proper asset accounts upon completion of the projects and record the corresponding depreciation.

The City Government :

Refund from the GF to SEF the amount of P25,440,815.54, representing payment of personal services to various casual City employees and the P6,698,767.81 total disbursements for travelling, training, medical expenses, gasoline and repairs and maintenance of motor vehicles and related expenses of various DepEd officials and public school teachers;

The City Local School Board (LSB):

Discontinue the practice of charging against the SEF, the payment of salaries, allowances and other benefits of clerks, administrative aides, laborer, librarians, drivers, security guards and drivers who are employed as casual employees of the City, regardless of their place of assignments to various public schools, as they are not included in the salaries and allowances for teachers/education personnel provided for under the laws and regulations that could be charged against the SEF.  Such expenses are  chargeable to the general fund of the City subject to existing auditing rules and regulations;

Refrain from utilizing the SEF for the payment of travelling and training expenses of DepEd officials, annual medical examination of public teachers, gasoline expenses and repair and maintenance of motor vehicles assigned to various DepEd officials, and other similar expenses of the mentioned national government employees considering that the SEF cannot be legally disbursed for the payment of expenses outside of the items of expenditures chargeable against the SEF as enumerated under Section 272 of RA 7160 and its IRR and DECS, DBM and DILG JC Nos.  01-, 01-A and 01-B;  and

Henceforth, restrict the allocation and prioritization of the SEF to the programs and projects specifically defined under the afore-stated law, rules and regulations in order to maximize the benefits that the public elementary and secondary schools could derive from this fund.

The City LSB:

Utilize the allocated funds for the programs and projects intended for the construction and maintenance of public school without delay rather than placing SEF funds in fixed term TD;

Stop the practice of delegating the LSB duties and responsibilities as mandated under Section 98 of the LGC.

Consider the deficiencies noted by the Audit Group such as the lack of equipment, facilities and school buildings in various public high schools in the prioritization of projects to be funded out of the SEF;

Evaluate the existing needs of various public schools by under taking survey, dialogue and regular consultations with the principals, teachers and other stakeholders affected by the SEF utilization;  and

Facilitate the formulation of definite plans to include the above-mentioned deficiencies and immediately implement the same.

The Bids and Awards Committee (BAC):

Strictly comply with the requirements under DBM Circular Letter Nos.  2011-6, 2011-6A and 2013-14, to ensure inclusion of the City’s procurement activities for common-use supplies and equipment in the Consolidated APP-CSE, and afford complete and accurate projection by the PS-DBM of inventory requirements of government;

Submit its Annual Procurement Plan for common-use supplies and equipment (APP-CSE) on or before November 30 of each year to DBM using the modified format as provided under DBM Circular Letter No.  2013-14.  This will help the DBM to anticipate the volume of demand for the different common-use supplies of the government for the ensuing year;

Take advantage of the services of the PS-DBM in the procurement of common-use supplies because aside from being required by the RIRR of RA 9184, this will enhance the City Government’s efficiency and economy as this will free the agency from the tediousness of attending to recurring transactions, and provide greater time for the procurement of high value, highly specialized requirements for its more significant projects;  and

In case of non-availability of items in the PS-DBM, procurement of common-use goods should be done in bulk quantities to avoid piecemeal purchases and splitting of purchase order.

For the BAC Secretariat:

Submit copies of (a) Invitation to Bid posted in PhilGEPS website, (b) Minutes of bid opening and preliminary evaluation of bids, (c) Bid Evaluation Report, (d) Post Qualification and Evaluation Report, (e) Invitation to observers, of all procurement projects;

Comply the minimum mandatory requirements enumerated in Item 9.1 of COA Circular No.  2012-001, particularly on supporting the disbursement voucher with documents that emanate from that Commit-tee such as the Invitation to Bid posted in Phil-GEPS website, minutes of bid opening and preliminary evaluation of bids, Bid Evaluation Report, Post Qualification and Evaluation Report and Invitation to Observers;

For the BAC:

Require the awarded bidders to submit the documents identified as deficient.  Transactions with noted deficiencies and/or with lacking documents will be suspended in audit if not corrected or submitted;

Henceforth, undertake strict and careful post qualification and evaluation of the documents submitted to ensure that contracts are awarded to eligible and responsive bidders pursuant to Section 12 of the IRR of RA 9184;  and

For the City Accountant:

Ensure completeness of required supporting documents to the disbursement voucher prior to its approval as prescribed in Section 4(6) of PD 1445 and COA Circular No.  2012-001 dated June 14, 2012.

We recommended that the BAC:

Include in the contract agreement with the winning bidder the warranty provision as mandated under Section 62 of the IRR of RA 9184;

Require the supplier/contractor to post warranty security for a year from the date of the issuance of Certificate of Acceptance as prescribed in the same section of the IRR of RA 9184 to protect the City’s interest against defects in the procurement of goods and infrastructure;  and

Coordinate with the City Legal Office and the City Treasury Office for the implementation of the warranty provision under Section 62 of the IRR of RA 9184 so that the supplier/ contractor would post the warranty security before the release of payment and attach copy of the warranty security documents to the disbursement voucher.

2.13	We recommended that the City Accounting Office:
Obtain from the bank and the City Treasurer’s Office all the necessary documents needed to support the identified reconciling items and draw Journal Entry Vouchers (JEV) to record all valid reconciling items that require adjustment and correction in the GL for fair presentation of the Cash in Bank account balance;
Analyze the prior years’ records and account for the unreconciled prior years’ discrepancy;
Request the LBP to submit the bank statements (BS) pertaining to the 4 other bank accounts in accordance with Section 74, Chapter 3 of P.D.  1445 to be able to reconcile the same with the GL and to prepare the corresponding BRS. Henceforth, request from the depository banks timely submission of BS to facilitate preparation of BRS;  and
Prepare the BRS on a regular basis and submit within ten days from receipt of BS pursuant to COA Circular No. 96-011 dated October 2, 1996.

6.14	We also recommended that the City Accounting Office (CAO):
Gather all supporting documents to record all assets mentioned which were found to be included in the RPCPPE but not recorded in the books of accounts;
Immediately looked into the noted discrepancies and determine the factors that contributed to the total variance of P407,662,577.64;
Continuously analyze the reconciling items in the PPE account and accordingly prepare correcting journal entries to reflect the correct balances of the affected accounts;
